## Playwright E2E Testing

### Setup
```bash
npm install -D @playwright/test
npx playwright install
```

### Test Structure
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test.describe('Critical: User Authentication', () => {
  test('login flow succeeds with valid credentials', async ({ page }) => {
    await page.goto('/login');
    await page.fill('[name=email]', 'user@example.com');
    await page.fill('[name=password]', 'password123');
    await page.click('[type=submit]');
    await expect(page).toHaveURL('/dashboard');
    await expect(page.locator('h1')).toContainText('Welcome');
  });
});
```

### What to Test with E2E
- Critical user flows (auth, checkout, onboarding)
- Error states (network fail, invalid input)
- Responsive breakpoints (mobile vs desktop)
- Cross-browser (Chrome, Firefox, Safari via Playwright)

### What NOT to Test with E2E
- Unit logic (use unit tests; faster)
- Visual pixel perfection (use visual regression)
- Every edge case (E2E is slow; test happy path + main errors)

### CI Integration
```yaml
- name: Run E2E Tests
  run: npx playwright test --reporter=html
- name: Upload Report
  uses: actions/upload-artifact@v3
  with:
    path: playwright-report/
```

### Checklist
- [ ] All critical user flows have E2E coverage
- [ ] Tests use `getByRole`/`getByLabel` (not CSS selectors)
- [ ] Tests run in CI on every PR
- [ ] Flaky tests quarantined and fixed within 1 sprint
